pmc BMC Public Health BMC Public Health 63 bmcph BMC Public Health 1471-2458 BMC PMC12487034 PMC12487034.1 12487034 12487034 41029292 10.1186/s12889-025-24523-0 24523 1 Research Patients’ knowledge, attitude, and practice regarding alopecia: a cross-sectional study in Hebei, China Li Huizheng 1 Yang Wenhui 1 Cheng Xingjian 1 Zhang Wen 1 Liu Liu 37700449@hebmu.edu.cn 2 Yang Lei 37900674@hebmu.edu.cn 1 1 https://ror.org/04eymdx19 grid.256883.2 0000 0004 1760 8442 Department of Burn and Plastic Surgery, Hebei Medical University Third Hospital, 2 https://ror.org/015ycqv20 grid.452702.6 0000 0004 1804 3009 Department of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery, The Second Hospital of Hebei Medical University, 30 9 2025 2025 25 478168 3194 8 5 2024 20 8 2025 30 09 2025 02 10 2025 02 10 2025 © The Author(s) 2025 2025 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Background More comprehensive knowledge about alopecia may translate into better patient management. This study aimed to investigate the knowledge, attitude, and practice (KAP) toward alopecia among patients with alopecia. Methods This cross-sectional study was conducted among patients with alopecia at Hebei Medical University Third Hospital between December 2023 and January 2024, using a researcher-developed questionnaire. Stress was analyzed using the perceived stress scale (PSS). Participants were recruited through convenience sampling. Structural equation modeling (SEM) was employed to test the hypothesized pathways between demographic/clinical factors and KAP variables. Results A total of 615 participants initially completed the questionnaire, and 545 valid responses were retained, yielding an effective response rate of 88.62%. The mean PSS and KAP scores were 42.48 ± 5.31 (possible scores of 14–70; 60.69%), 11.29 ± 6.42 (possible scores of 0–28; 40.32%), 32.51 ± 3.82 (possible scores of 10–50; 65.02%), and 26.44 ± 6.07 (possible scores of 10–50; 72.88%), respectively. The SEM showed that knowledge was influenced by hair loss after COVID-19 (β=-0.023, P P P P P P P P P Conclusion Patients with alopecia have poor knowledge, negative attitudes, and proactive practices toward alopecia, which was influenced by their age, COVID-19 infection, changes in hair loss after COVID-19, medications that cause hair loss, polycystic ovary syndrome, and years of alopecia. In addition, since knowledge influences attitude and practice, improving knowledge through educational activities should also improve practice, possibly translating into more benefits for patients. Running Title Patients’ KAP toward alopecia Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1186/s12889-025-24523-0. Keywords Alopecia Stress Knowledge, attitude, practice Cross-sectional study Medical Science Research Project of the Health Commission of Hebei Province 20221187 20221187 Liu Liu Yang Lei pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © BioMed Central Ltd., part of Springer Nature 2025 Background Alopecia is the loss of hair in an area where it is expected to be present [ 1 2 1 2 1 2 1 2 3 1 4 5 6 7 1 2 6 7 Knowledge, attitude, and practice (KAP) studies provide quantitative and qualitative data about the gaps, misconceptions, and misunderstandings of a specific population toward a specific subject [ 8 9 10 11 12 13 14 15 Methods Study design and participants This cross-sectional study was conducted among patients with alopecia at Hebei Medical University Third Hospital between December 2023 and January 2024. The inclusion criteria were (1) age between 18 and 60 years, (2) diagnosed with alopecia by physicians, and (3) ability to cooperate to complete the questionnaire. The exclusion criteria were (1) mental disorders, reading disabilities, or other conditions impeding questionnaire completion, or (2) inability to use smartphones and, consequently, inability to complete the questionnaire. Ethical approval for this study was obtained from the Medical Ethics Committee of Hebei Medical University Third Hospital (approval NO: 2023-114-1). Written informed consent was obtained from all participants before they completed the questionnaire. Questionnaire design The questionnaire was designed by the investigators based on the 2019 Chinese Guidelines for Diagnosis and Treatment of Androgenetic Alopecia released by the Hair Aesthetics Professional Committee of the Chinese Medical Association’s Aesthetic and Plastic Physicians Branch. After design, modifications were made based on the opinions of three dermatology experts and two experts in the field of esthetic medicine. A pilot study was conducted with a small sample size (37 participants), yielding a Cronbach’s α coefficient of 0.939, indicating acceptable internal consistency. The final questionnaire, administered in Chinese (The version that translated into English was attached as an Appendix), comprises four sections: demographic information (gender, age, etc.), knowledge dimension, attitude dimension, and practice dimension. The knowledge dimension comprised 14 items, scored as 2 points for very understanding, 1 point for somewhat understanding, and 0 points for not understanding, with a score range of 0–28. The attitude dimension consisted of 10 questions, using a five-point Likert scale ranging from strongly agree to strongly disagree, scored from 5 to 1, with a score range of 10–50. The practice dimension included 11 questions, with 11 being multiple-choice questions analyzed using an upset plot and others using a five-point Likert scale, scored from always to never (5 to 1), with a score range of 10–50. Scores < 70% were considered poor [ 16 The stress levels were measured using the perceived stress scale (PSS), which was proposed by Cohen et al. in 1983 [ 17 18 Questionnaire distribution and quality control Convenience sampling was used in this study. Eligible individuals included patients who either presented to our clinic with alopecia during the study period or were members of a hospital-managed WeChat group specifically established for alopecia patients. A dedicated research team was established specifically for this study, composed of trained clinical staff. During the recruitment process, team members systematically invited eligible patients by distributing a QR code linked to the electronic questionnaire. In the outpatient setting, this was done face-to-face at the time of clinical consultation. For the online group, the QR code and study explanation were posted in the WeChat group. In both recruitment channels, the research team provided a standardized verbal or written explanation of the study’s purpose, procedures, and voluntary nature. A given IP address could be used to submit a questionnaire only once. All questions were mandatory to submit a questionnaire. The research team rigorously examined all submissions for completeness, internal consistency, and logical coherence. Investigators were well-versed in understanding the research questions and the survey process, which enhanced data accuracy and consistency. Questionnaires exhibiting logical errors, incomplete responses, or uniform answers across all items were categorized as invalid. Sample size calculation The sample size was calculated using the formula for cross-sectional studies: α = 0.05, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
