ecia have poor knowledge, negative attitudes, and proactive practices toward alopecia. The SEM showed knowledge influences attitude and practice. The results may help design educational interventions that could translate into better patient outcomes. The exact pathogenesis of alopecia is unknown, but it is likely due to a multifactorial genetic predisposition triggered by environmental factors [ 1 2 19 The present study revealed poor knowledge and attitude toward alopecia but practice was better, suggesting that the patients perform specific actions out of habit or following instructions without understanding why. Although few studies specifically examined the comprehensive KAP toward alopecia, a study reported that patients with alopecia in Iran had poor knowledge of their disease [ 10 20 15 11 13 14 The SEM analysis revealed that knowledge influenced attitude and practice (both directly and indirectly) and that attitude influenced practice. Hence, designing and implementing educational interventions to improve knowledge should also improve attitudes and practices toward alopecia. Specifically, knowledge about normal hair loss, causes of hair loss, lifestyle habits affecting hair loss, medications causing hair loss, and management of hair loss should be emphasized. Of note, a KAP study of general practitioners in Saudi Arabia revealed a poor knowledge of alopecia [ 12 21 22 23 The SEM analysis also showed that hair loss after COVID-19, age, and taking medication that causes hair loss were negatively associated with knowledge of alopecia. COVID-19 itself does not cause hair loss, but telogen effluvium (i.e., hair loss due to stressful events) has been reported in patients after COVID-19 [ 24 19 25 This study has limitations. The participants were from a single center using convenience sampling, limiting the generalizability of the results to a single geographical area. The cross-sectional nature of the study allowed the determination of KAP at a single point in time. Whether the KAP will change in time remains to be determined. Nevertheless, the present study could serve as a historical baseline to examine the effect of educational interventions. In addition, causality cannot be determined using cross-sectional studies. The SEM analyses can provide a surrogate of causality, but it must be remembered that the causality is statistically inferred instead of being observed [ 26 28 29 30 In conclusion, patients with alopecia have poor knowledge, negative attitudes, and proactive practices toward alopecia. Since knowledge influences attitude and practice, as shown by the SEM, improving knowledge through educational activities should also improve practice, possibly translating into better patient outcomes. Future studies could examine the effect of such interventions. Supplementary Information  Supplementary Material 1.  Supplementary Material 2. Abbreviations KAP Knowledge, Attitude, Practice PSS Perceived Stress Scale SEM Structural Equation Modeling COVID-19 Coronavirus Disease 2019 PCOS Polycystic Ovary Syndrome JAK Janus Kinase SPSS Statistical Package for the Social Sciences AMOS Analysis of Moment Structures SD Standard Deviation CI Confidence Interval ANOVA Analysis of Variance BMI Body Mass Index RMB Renminbi (Chinese currency) WHO World Health Organization HINTS Health Information National Trends Survey Publisher’s Note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Huizheng Li and Wenhui Yang contributed equally to this work. Acknowledgements The authors acknowledge the help and support of all the participants and the members of the Department of Burn and Plastic Surgery, Hebei Medical University Third Hospital. Authors’ contributions Huizheng Li and Wenhui Yang carried out the studies, participated in collecting data, and drafted the manuscript. Xingjian Cheng and Wen Zhang performed the statistical analysis and participated in its design. Lei Yang an